    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">🧠</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Trauma & Stressor / OCD-Related</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Obsessions and/or compulsions present.</li><li><strong>Obsessions:</strong> recurrent, intrusive, persistent unwanted thoughts, urges, or images.</li><li>Person attempts to ignore, suppress, or neutralize the thoughts.</li><li><strong>Compulsions:</strong> repetitive behaviors or mental acts performed in response to obsessions or rigid rules.</li><li>Behaviors aim to reduce distress or prevent a dreaded event, though they are excessive or unrealistic.</li><li>Time-consuming (&gt;1 hour/day) or cause clinically significant distress or impairment</li><li><strong>Common foci of obsessions:</strong> contamination, responsibility for harm, sex and morality, violence, religion, symmetry or order</li><li><strong>Common compulsive rituals:</strong> decontamination, checking, repeating routine activities, ordering/arranging, mental rituals</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Lifetime prevalence ~ 1.3%</li><li><strong>Gender:</strong> slightly more common in women</li><li><strong>Age of onset:</strong> childhood or early adolescence.</li><li><strong>Course:</strong> chronic without treatment.</li><li><strong>Comorbidity:</strong> depression, anxiety disorders, substance use disorders.</li><li>~33% show hoarding symptoms; ~75% experience an anxiety disorder at some point.</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors / Etiology</h3><h4>Biological:</h4><ul><li><strong>Heritability:</strong> 0.40–0.50.</li><li><strong>Neurotransmitter:</strong> serotonin implicated.</li><li><strong>Brain circuit:</strong> cortico-striatal-thalamic-cortical (CSTC) loop.</li><li><strong>Key regions:</strong> orbitofrontal cortex, caudate nucleus, anterior cingulate cortex.</li></ul><h4>Psychological:</h4><ul><li><strong>Behavioral model:</strong> compulsions become conditioned habits that persist after threat disappears.</li><li><strong>Cognitive distortions:</strong> thought-action fusion; inflated responsibility for harm; belief that thinking about an event increases its likelihood.</li><li>OCD risk emphasizes harm responsibility and threat misinterpretation.</li></ul><h4>Social / Environmental:</h4><ul><li>Stressful life events may trigger symptom onset.</li><li>Cultural context shapes content of obsessions (e.g., religion).</li></ul><h3>Evidence-Based Treatments</h3><ul><li>Psychotherapy (First-line) – Exposure and Response Prevention (ERP)</li><li>Exposure to feared stimuli.</li><li>Prevention of compulsive ritual.</li><li>Promotes extinction of conditioned anxiety.</li><li>Delivered through hierarchical exposure.</li><li>ERP produces significant improvement in ~69–75% of patients.</li><li><strong>Medication – First line:</strong> SSRIs (fluoxetine, sertraline); Alt: clomipramine (tricyclic antidepressant); SNRIs sometimes used off-label.</li><li><strong>Key:</strong> Stop rituals, face fears, break negative reinforcement</li><li>ERP produces significant improvement in ~69–75% of patients.</li><li>Harmful / Ineffective Approaches  Reassurance seeking or avoidance behaviors (reinforce compulsions).</li></ul><h3>Predictors of Outcomes</h3><h4>Better outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>Good insight into irrationality of obsessions/compulsions</li><li>Strong engagement in Exposure and Response Prevention (ERP)</li><li>Lower baseline symptom severity</li><li>Strong social support</li><li>Later age of onset (adult onset tends to be less chronic)</li></ul><h4>Worse outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>Early onset (childhood or adolescence)</li><li>Severe compulsions and ritual complexity</li><li>Comorbid disorders (especially major depression, tic disorders, or substance use)</li><li>Poor insight or overvalued beliefs about obsessions</li><li>High avoidance or reassurance-seeking behaviors (maintain the fear cycle)</li></ul><h4>Course pattern:</h4><ul><li>Typically chronic without treatment</li><li>Symptoms often fluctuate with stressful life events</li><li>Effective treatment (ERP + SSRIs) produces substantial improvement in ~69–75% of patients.</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li>OCD risk emphasizes harm responsibility and threat misinterpretation.</li><li><strong>vs. BDD:</strong> BDD obsessions are restricted to perceived appearance defects; OCD obsessions involve multiple domains (contamination, harm, morality, symmetry, religion).</li><li><strong>vs. Hoarding Disorder:</strong> OCD hoarding occurs due to specific obsessional fears (e.g., losing something important or causing harm); hoarding disorder involves persistent difficulty discarding possessions and emotional attachment to items, independent of specific obsessions.</li><li><strong>vs. GAD:</strong> GAD involves excessive worry across many real-life domains; OCD involves intrusive, irrational obsessions and compulsive rituals performed to reduce distress.</li><li><strong>vs. OCPD:</strong> OCD symptoms are ego-dystonic (experienced as intrusive and unwanted); OCPD involves ego-syntonic perfectionism, rigidity, and control without intrusive obsessions or compulsive rituals.</li><li><strong>vs. Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD):</strong> ASD repetitive behaviors are related to routine, sensory regulation, or restricted interests; OCD compulsions are performed to reduce anxiety triggered by intrusive obsessions.</li><li><strong>vs. Tic Disorders/Tourette’s:</strong> tics are sudden, involuntary motor or vocal behaviors not linked to obsessions; OCD compulsions are goal-directed behaviors performed to neutralize anxiety.</li><li><strong>vs. Psychotic Disorders:</strong> OCD intrusive thoughts are recognized as irrational or excessive (some insight present); psychotic delusions are fixed false beliefs without insight.</li></ul>
      </div>
