    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">🪞</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Body Dysmorphic Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Trauma & Stressor / OCD-Related</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Preoccupation with ≥1 perceived defects in appearance.</li><li>Defects appear slight or unobservable to others.</li><li>Repetitive behaviors or mental acts (mirror checking, reassurance seeking, excessive grooming).</li><li>Concerns not limited to weight/body fat (otherwise eating disorder).</li></ul><h4>Additional—</h4><ul><li>Concerns occupy ~3–8 hours/day on average.</li><li>Women often focus on skin, hips, breasts, legs.</li><li>Men often focus on height, body hair, muscularity, genital size.</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Lifetime prevalence ~3%</li><li><strong>Gender:</strong> slightly more common in women.</li><li><strong>Age of onset:</strong> adolescence.</li><li><strong>Comorbidity:</strong> depression, anxiety disorders, substance use disorders.</li><li>~33% meet criteria for OCD.</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors / Etiology</h3><h4>Biological:</h4><ul><li><strong>Heritability:</strong> 0.40–0.50 (same as OCD).</li><li>Brain systems overlap with OCD-related disorders.</li></ul><h4>Psychological:</h4><ul><li><strong>Detail-focused visual processing:</strong> attention to small features rather than overall appearance.</li><li><strong>Cognitive bias:</strong> exaggerated importance of attractiveness for self-worth.</li></ul><h4>Social / Environmental</h4><ul><li>Appearance-related teasing or criticism, particularly in youth</li><li>Cultural emphasis on physical attractiveness.</li><li><strong>Unique feature:</strong> distorted attention to appearance details.</li></ul><h3>Evidence-Based Treatment</h3><ul><li>Psychotherapy (First-Line) - Exposure and Response Prevention (ERP) = Exposure to feared appearance situations  Prevention of reassurance behaviors (e.g., mirror checking).</li><li><strong>Medication:</strong> Same as OCD = SSRIs commonly used</li><li>Harmful / Ineffective Approaches  Cosmetic surgery typically does not reduce symptoms.</li></ul><h3>Predictors of Outcomes</h3><h4>Better outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>Higher insight into appearance concerns being exaggerated</li><li>Engagement in CBT with exposure and response prevention</li><li>Lower baseline symptom severity</li><li>Strong therapeutic alliance and treatment adherence</li></ul><h4>Worse outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>Poor insight or delusional beliefs about appearance defects</li><li>Frequent mirror checking, reassurance seeking, or camouflaging behaviors</li><li>History of appearance-related bullying or criticism</li><li>Comorbid depression, anxiety disorders, or OCD</li></ul><h4>Course pattern:</h4><ul><li>Often chronic if untreated</li><li>Symptoms frequently worsen during adolescence or early adulthood</li><li>Cosmetic procedures rarely improve symptoms and may reinforce the disorder</li></ul><h4>Important risk indicator:</h4><ul><li>Elevated suicide risk compared with many other anxiety-related disorders.</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. OCD:</strong> OCD obsessions involve many possible themes; BDD obsessions are restricted to perceived physical defects in appearance.</li><li><strong>vs. Eating Disorders (e.g., Anorexia Nervosa):</strong> eating disorders involve preoccupation with weight, body fat, and shape related to eating behaviors; BDD focuses on specific body features (e.g., nose, skin, hair) and concerns are not limited to weight or body fat.</li><li><strong>vs. Social Anxiety D:</strong> social anxiety involves fear of negative evaluation or embarrassment in social situations; BDD avoidance is due to belief that appearance flaws are visible and judged by others.</li><li><strong>vs. Delusional Disorder (Somatic Type):</strong> BDD may involve poor insight but beliefs can fluctuate; delusional disorder involves fixed, unshakeable belief about a bodily defect.</li><li><strong>vs. Normal Appearance Concerns:</strong> normal dissatisfaction with appearance does not cause hours of preoccupation or significant impairment; BDD involves persistent preoccupation and repetitive behaviors such as mirror checking.</li><li><strong>vs. MDD:</strong> depressive rumination may include negative body image; BDD involves specific obsessive preoccupation with perceived defects and repetitive appearance-checking behaviors.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">📦</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Hoarding Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Trauma & Stressor / OCD-Related</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Persistent difficulty discarding possessions regardless of value.</li><li>Perceived need to save items.</li><li>Distress associated with discarding.</li><li>Accumulation clutters living spaces and interferes with intended use.</li></ul><h4>Additional—</h4><ul><li>Excessive acquiring behaviors.</li><li>Strong emotional attachment to possessions.</li><li>Many individuals lack insight into severity.</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Lifetime prevalence ~1.5% -- rougher estimate due to insight</li><li><strong>Gender:</strong> roughly equal.</li><li><strong>Age of onset:</strong> childhood or early adolescence; worsens with age.</li><li><strong>Comorbidity:</strong> depression, anxiety disorders, substance use disorders.</li><li><strong>Overlap:</strong> ~25% meet criteria for OCD.</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors / Etiology</h3><h4>Biological:</h4><ul><li><strong>Heritability:</strong> 0.40–0.50 (same as OCD and BDD).</li><li>Brain regions overlapping with OCD-related disorders.</li></ul><h4>Psychological:</h4><ul><li>Cognitive deficits:</li><li>poor organization</li><li>difficulty categorizing items</li><li>difficulty making decisions about possessions.</li><li><strong>Beliefs about possessions:</strong> objects may have future value or emotional meaning.</li></ul><h4>Social / Environmental:</h4><ul><li>Reinforcement of saving behaviors.</li><li>Cultural beliefs about waste and resource preservation.</li><li><strong>Unique feature:</strong> emotional attachment to objects and decision-making deficits.</li></ul><h3>Evidence-Based Treatment</h3><ul><li>Psychotherapy (First-Line) – Modified Exposure and Response Prevention:</li><li>Exposure to discarding possessions.</li><li>Prevention of hoarding rituals.</li><li>Includes motivational interviewing and organizational training.</li><li>Often includes in-home decluttering sessions.</li><li><strong>Medication:</strong> Same medication classes as OCD (SSRIs), though less evidence of effectiveness.</li><li>Harmful / Ineffective Approaches  Forced clean-outs without therapy → often relapse.</li></ul><h3>Predictors of Outcomes</h3><h4>Better outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>Greater insight into the severity of clutter</li><li>Motivation to change and willingness to discard possessions</li><li>Participation in specialized hoarding-focused CBT (including in-home interventions)</li><li>Strong social or family support</li></ul><h4>Worse outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>Poor insight or denial about hoarding severity</li><li>Strong emotional attachment to possessions</li><li>Severe clutter that significantly limits living space</li><li>Comorbid depression or anxiety disorders</li></ul><h4>Course pattern:</h4><ul><li>Typically chronic and progressively worsening over time</li><li>Often begins in childhood or adolescence, but impairment becomes severe in adulthood</li><li>Symptoms frequently worsen with major life stressors or trauma</li></ul><h4>Treatment response pattern:</h4><ul><li>Hoarding disorder tends to show weaker response to medication compared with OCD</li><li>Improvement usually requires long-term behavioral intervention and environmental change.</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. OCD:</strong> OCD hoarding is driven by specific obsessions (e.g., fear of losing important information or contamination); hoarding disorder involves difficulty discarding possessions due to emotional attachment or perceived usefulness, not obsessional fear.</li><li><strong>vs. Major Neurocognitive Disorder (Dementia):</strong> clutter in dementia arises from memory impairment and executive dysfunction; hoarding disorder involves intentional saving behaviors and distress when discarding items.</li><li><strong>vs. MDD:</strong> clutter may accumulate due to low motivation or neglect in depression; hoarding disorder involves active acquisition and distress about discarding possessions.</li><li><strong>vs. Normal Collecting Behavior:</strong> collectors organize and display items systematically; hoarding disorder results in disorganized accumulation that compromises living spaces.</li><li><strong>vs. Psychotic Disorders:</strong> hoarding due to psychosis may be driven by delusional beliefs about objects; hoarding disorder involves attachment and perceived usefulness rather than delusions.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">⚠️</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Post-Traumatic-Stress Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Trauma & Stressor / OCD-Related</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Exposure to actual or threatened death, serious injury, or sexual violence (directly, witnessing, learning about it happening to close others, or repeated exposure to traumatic details).</li></ul><h4>Symptoms from four clusters:</h4><ul><li><strong>Intrusion (≥1):</strong> intrusive memories, nightmares, flashbacks, distress to trauma cues</li><li><strong>Avoidance (≥1):</strong> avoiding trauma-related thoughts, feelings, or reminders</li><li><strong>Negative cognition/mood (≥2):</strong> negative beliefs, guilt or shame, detachment, reduced interest in activities</li><li><strong>Arousal/reactivity (≥2):</strong> hypervigilance, exaggerated startle, irritability, sleep or concentration problems</li><li>Symptoms last &gt;1 month, cause distress or impairment, and are not due to substances or medical conditions.</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>About 2/3 report at least one lifetime trauma</li><li><strong>Lifetime prevalence:</strong> ~3–6%</li><li>3.9% in general population; 5.6% of those exposed to trauma</li><li>Women ≈ 1.5-2× more likely than men</li><li>About 2/3 meet criteria for an anxiety disorder by age 21;</li><li>93% meet criteria for another disorder before onset; depression, anxiety, SUD, personality</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors – Biological</h3><ul><li>Shared genetic vulnerability with anxiety disorders</li><li>Hyperactive amygdala → heightened fear responses</li><li>Reduced medial prefrontal cortex activity → impaired fear regulation</li><li>Reduced hippocampal functioning → difficulty placing threat memories in context)</li><li>Genetic vulnerability to stress sensitivity</li><li>Stress hormone (HPA axis) dysregulation</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors — Psychological</h3><ul><li><strong>Learning:</strong> Mowrer’s two-factor model – operant  classical conditioning (avoidance = negative reinforcement)</li><li>High anxiety sensitivity or neuroticism</li><li>Poor emotion regulation or coping skills</li><li>Cognitive biases such as self-blame and catastrophic interpretation of trauma</li></ul><h4>Trauma-Specific Factors:</h4><ul><li>Severity of trauma increases risk</li><li>Human-caused trauma (e.g., assault, war, rape) more likely to cause PTSD than natural disasters</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors — Sociocultural</h3><ul><li>prior trauma exposure</li><li>limited social support</li><li>maladaptive coping (avoidance, dissociation)</li><li>cultural context influencing trauma interpretation</li><li><strong>Risk is elevated among:</strong> refugees and individuals exposed to war or violence, individuals with prior psychiatric diagnoses, those exposed to repeated or interpersonal trauma</li></ul><h3>Empirically Supported Treatments</h3><h4>Psychotherapy (first-line)</h4><ul><li>Prolonged Exposure Therapy</li><li>typically 8–15 sessions (~90 minutes each)</li><li>repeated exposure to trauma memories and cues</li><li>goal: extinction of conditioned fear response</li><li>Cognitive Processing Therapy (CPT)</li><li>CBT-based approach</li><li>focuses on reducing guilt, shame, and distorted trauma beliefs</li><li>EMDR (Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing)</li><li>trauma recall paired with guided eye movements</li><li>mechanism likely exposure-based rather than eye-movement-specific</li></ul><h4>Medication</h4><ul><li>SSRIs (FDA-approved):</li><li>– sertraline (Zoloft)</li><li>– paroxetine (Paxil)</li></ul><h4>Notes:</h4><ul><li>relapse common when medication is stopped</li><li>benzodiazepines often prescribed but not supported by evidence</li></ul><h3>Predictors of Outcome</h3><h4>Better outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>strong social support</li><li>effective coping strategies</li><li>higher cognitive functioning</li><li>ability to process trauma memories</li></ul><h4>Worse outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>repeated trauma</li><li>avoidance coping</li><li>dissociation</li><li>prior psychiatric disorders</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. Acute Stress Disorder:</strong> PTSD symptoms last &gt;1 month; ASD occurs 3 days–1 month after trauma.</li><li><strong>vs. Adjustment Disorder:</strong> adjustment disorder occurs after stressful life events not involving severe trauma (threat of death, injury, or sexual violence).</li><li><strong>vs. Major Depressive Disorder:</strong> MDD involves persistent low mood and anhedonia; PTSD includes trauma-specific re-experiencing, avoidance, and hyperarousal.</li><li><strong>vs. Panic Disorder:</strong> panic attacks in panic disorder are unexpected; PTSD panic occurs when exposed to trauma reminders.</li><li><strong>vs. Dissociative Disorders:</strong> dissociation may occur in PTSD, but PTSD also includes intrusion and hyperarousal symptoms linked to trauma.</li><li><strong>vs. Traumatic Brain Injury:</strong> TBI may produce cognitive and emotional symptoms similar to PTSD, but does not involve trauma-related intrusion and avoidance patterns.</li><li><strong>vs. Psychotic Disorders:</strong> PTSD flashbacks involve trauma-related memories and triggers; psychotic hallucinations or delusions are not tied to trauma reminders.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">⏱️</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Acute Stress Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Trauma & Stressor / OCD-Related</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Exposure to actual or threatened death, serious injury, or sexual violence (same trauma requirement as PTSD).</li><li>Symptoms similar to PTSD but include broader symptom categories and do not need to fall into specific clusters.</li></ul><h4>Common symptoms include:</h4><ul><li>intrusive memories or flashbacks</li><li>dissociation (e.g., feeling detached or unreal)</li><li>avoidance of trauma reminders</li><li>anxiety and hyperarousal</li></ul><h4>Diagnostic requirements:</h4><ul><li>≥9 symptoms across categories</li><li>Duration: 3 days to 1 month after trauma</li><li>significant distress or impairment</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>symptoms common immediately after trauma</li><li>~90% of women report significant symptoms within 1 month after rape</li><li>less than half of ASD cases develop PTSD within 2 years</li></ul><h3>Etiology / Risk Factors</h3><h4>Biological</h4><ul><li>Same vulnerability factors as PTSD:</li><li>genetic risk for anxiety</li><li>heightened amygdala reactivity</li><li>stress-response dysregulation</li></ul><h4>Psychological</h4><ul><li>dissociation during trauma</li><li>avoidance coping</li><li>difficulty processing traumatic memories</li></ul><h4>Sociocultural</h4><ul><li>Same as PTSD:</li><li>trauma severity</li><li>interpersonal violence</li><li>limited social support</li></ul><h3>Empirically Supported Treatments</h3><ul><li>Brief CBT after trauma</li><li>can reduce likelihood of developing PTSD</li><li>focuses on trauma processing and coping skills</li><li>Exposure-based interventions</li><li>similar mechanisms to PTSD treatments</li><li>Medication is not primary treatment.</li></ul><h3>Predictors of Outcome</h3><h4>Higher PTSD risk when:</h4><ul><li>trauma is severe or interpersonal</li><li>strong avoidance coping is present</li><li>dissociation occurs during trauma</li></ul><h4>Protective factors:</h4><ul><li>social support</li><li>adaptive coping strategies</li><li>ability to process trauma memories</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. PTSD:</strong> ASD duration 3 days–1 month; PTSD &gt;1 month.</li><li><strong>vs. Adjustment Disorder:</strong> adjustment disorder follows stressful life events without extreme trauma exposure.</li><li><strong>vs. Normal Acute Stress Reaction:</strong> temporary distress after trauma is common; ASD requires ≥9 symptoms and functional impairment.</li><li><strong>vs. Dissociative Disorders:</strong> dissociation may occur in ASD but symptoms also include intrusion, avoidance, and hyperarousal tied to trauma.</li><li><strong>vs. Panic Disorder:</strong> panic attacks in ASD are trauma-triggered; panic disorder attacks are unexpected and recurrent.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">🧩</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Schizophrenia</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Schizophrenia Spectrum</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>For a diagnosis of schizophrenia, a person must have ≥2 symptoms, and one must be delusions, hallucinations, or disorganized speech:</li><li>delusions</li><li>hallucinations</li><li>disorganized speech</li><li>disorganized (or catatonic) behavior</li><li>negative symptoms (diminished motivation or emotional expression)</li></ul><h4>Additional requirements:</h4><ul><li>Active symptoms ≥1 month</li><li>Continuous disturbance for ≥6 months</li><li>Clinically significant impairment in functioning (work, relationships, self-care)</li></ul><h3>Clinical Description</h3><ul><li>Symptoms are typically grouped into three categories:</li></ul><h4>Positive symptoms</h4><ul><li>Excesses or distortions of normal functioning</li><li>delusions (false beliefs held despite contradictory evidence)</li><li>hallucinations (perceptions without external stimuli, often auditory)</li></ul><h4>Negative symptoms</h4><ul><li>Deficits in normal functioning</li><li>avolition – lack of motivation</li><li>asociality – reduced interest in social interaction</li><li>anhedonia – reduced ability to experience pleasure</li><li>blunted affect – reduced emotional expression</li><li>alogia – poverty of speech</li></ul><h4>Disorganized symptoms</h4><ul><li>disorganized speech (loose associations, derailment)</li><li>disorganized behavior</li><li>cognitive impairment in attention and executive functioning</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Lifetime prevalence ≈ 1%</li><li>Gender: slightly more common in men</li><li>Typical onset: late adolescence or early adulthood</li><li>Onset occurs earlier in men than women</li><li>Course:</li><li>usually involves repeated acute episodes with residual symptoms between episodes</li><li>Other important statistics:</li><li>people with schizophrenia are 12× more likely to die by suicide than the general population</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors – Biological</h3><ul><li>Heritability ≈ .77–.81</li></ul><h4>Brain structure and function</h4><ul><li>reduced hippocampal volume</li><li>smaller volumes in amygdala, thalamus, and basal ganglia</li></ul><h4>Brain connectivity</h4><ul><li>reduced connectivity between brain networks</li><li>reduced frontoparietal and default-mode network connectivity</li><li>associated with cognitive impairment and negative symptoms</li></ul><h4>Dopamine theory - DISMISSED</h4><h3>Risk Factors — Psychological</h3><ul><li>cognitive deficits in attention, memory, and executive functioning</li><li>abnormal interpretation of internal experiences leading to delusions or hallucinations</li><li>Cognitive-behavioral models suggest:</li><li>individuals may attempt to interpret unusual perceptual experiences, leading to delusional belief systems</li></ul><h3>Risk Factors — Sociocultural</h3><ul><li>Early developmental risk factors include:</li><li>obstetrical complications during pregnancy or birth</li><li>maternal infections during pregnancy</li><li>prenatal stress exposure</li><li>Example risk factor:</li><li>maternal exposure to Toxoplasma gondii associated with ~2.5× increased risk of schizophrenia in offspring</li><li>Environmental influences interact with genetic vulnerability.</li></ul><h3>Empirically Supported Treatments</h3><h4>Medication (first-line)</h4><ul><li>Antipsychotic medications</li></ul><h4>Two major classes:</h4><ul><li>first-generation antipsychotics (e.g., haloperidol)</li><li>second-generation antipsychotics (e.g., clozapine, olanzapine)</li><li>Medications primarily reduce positive symptoms.</li></ul><h4>Psychotherapy</h4><ul><li>Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT)</li><li>helps patients evaluate delusional beliefs</li><li>reduces symptom severity and distress</li><li>produces small to moderate improvements across symptoms and functioning</li><li>Cognitive Behavioral Social Skills Training (CBSST)</li><li>combines CBT and social skills training</li><li>typically lasts 6–9 months</li><li>Comprehensive early intervention programs (e.g., NAVIGATE)</li><li>combine medication, therapy, family support, and vocational help</li></ul><h3>Predictors of Outcome</h3><h4>Better outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>earlier treatment after psychosis onset</li><li>strong social support</li><li>adherence to medication and therapy</li><li>participation in comprehensive treatment programs</li></ul><h4>Worse outcomes associated with:</h4><ul><li>longer duration of untreated psychosis</li><li>severe negative symptoms</li><li>cognitive impairment</li><li>repeated episodes</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. Schizophreniform Disorder:</strong> </li><li>schizophreniform symptoms last 1–6 months; schizophrenia requires ≥6 months total disturbance.</li><li><strong>vs. Brief Psychotic Disorder:</strong> </li><li>psychotic symptoms last 1 day to &lt;1 month and full recovery occurs.</li><li><strong>vs. Schizoaffective Disorder:</strong> </li><li>requires major mood episode (depression or mania) occurring with psychotic symptoms.</li><li><strong>vs. Delusional Disorder:</strong> </li><li>delusions present but hallucinations, disorganized speech, and negative symptoms are absent or minimal.</li><li><strong>vs. Bipolar Disorder with Psychotic Features:</strong> </li><li>psychotic symptoms occur only during mood episodes.</li><li><strong>vs. Major Depressive Disorder with Psychotic Features:</strong> </li><li>psychotic symptoms occur only during depressive episodes.</li><li><strong>vs. Substance-Induced Psychotic Disorder:</strong> </li><li>psychosis caused by drug intoxication, withdrawal, or medication effects.</li><li><strong>vs. Autism Spectrum Disorder:</strong> </li><li>ASD involves lifelong social communication differences; schizophrenia involves new onset psychotic symptoms such as delusions and hallucinations.</li><li>Other Schizophrenia Spectrum Disorders</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">🔹</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Schizophreniform Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Schizophrenia Spectrum</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Same symptom criteria as schizophrenia:</li><li>≥2 symptoms, including one of:</li><li>delusions</li><li>hallucinations</li><li>disorganized speech</li><li>Duration:</li><li>≥1 month but &lt;6 months</li><li>Functional impairment not required.</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Less common than schizophrenia</li><li>Often diagnosed early in illness course</li></ul><h3>Etiology</h3><ul><li>Same biological and environmental risk factors as schizophrenia</li></ul><h3>Treatment</h3><ul><li>Antipsychotic medications</li><li>early intervention and CBT for psychosis</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. Brief Psychotic Disorder:</strong> &lt;1 month duration.</li><li><strong>vs. Schizophrenia:</strong> ≥6 months total disturbance.</li><li><strong>vs. Schizoaffective Disorder:</strong> includes major mood episodes.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">⚡</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Brief Psychotic Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Schizophrenia Spectrum</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Presence of ≥1 psychotic symptom:</li><li>delusions</li><li>hallucinations</li><li>disorganized speech</li><li>grossly disorganized or catatonic behavior</li><li>At least one must be delusions, hallucinations, or disorganized speech.</li><li>Duration:</li><li>≥1 day but &lt;1 month</li><li>full return to premorbid functioning</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Rare disorder</li><li>Often occurs following severe stress or trauma</li></ul><h3>Etiology</h3><ul><li>Severe psychosocial stressors</li><li>Genetic vulnerability to psychosis</li></ul><h3>Treatment</h3><ul><li>short-term antipsychotic medication</li><li>supportive psychotherapy</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. Schizophreniform Disorder:</strong> duration 1–6 months.</li><li><strong>vs. Schizophrenia:</strong> total disturbance ≥6 months.</li><li><strong>vs. Mood Disorders with Psychotic Features:</strong> psychosis occurs only during mood episodes.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">🌗</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Schizoaffective disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Schizophrenia Spectrum</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>Combination of psychotic symptoms and mood episodes.</li></ul><h4>Key requirement:</h4><ul><li>≥2 weeks of psychotic symptoms without mood symptoms</li></ul><h4>Specifier types:</h4><ul><li>bipolar type (mania present)</li><li>depressive type (major depression only)</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Less common than schizophrenia</li></ul><h3>Etiology</h3><ul><li>Combination of risk factors for schizophrenia and mood disorders</li></ul><h3>Treatment</h3><ul><li>Antipsychotics</li><li>mood stabilizers or antidepressants</li><li>psychotherapy</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. Schizophrenia:</strong> mood episodes not central in schizophrenia.</li><li><strong>vs. Bipolar Disorder with Psychotic Features:</strong> psychosis occurs only during mood episodes.</li><li><strong>vs. Major Depressive Disorder with Psychotic Features:</strong> psychosis occurs only during depressive episodes.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
    <article class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" aria-expanded="false">
        <span class="item-title-wrap">
          <span class="item-icon">🎯</span>
          <span>
            <span class="item-title">Delusional Disorder</span>
            <span class="item-subtitle">Schizophrenia Spectrum</span>
          </span>
        </span>
        <span class="chevron">▾</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-panel">
        <h3>DSM-5-TR Criteria</h3><ul><li>≥1 delusion lasting ≥1 month</li><li>Additional features:</li><li>Criterion A for schizophrenia not met</li><li>functioning relatively preserved</li><li>behavior not obviously bizarre</li></ul><h3>Epidemiology</h3><ul><li>Rare disorder</li><li>onset usually middle adulthood</li></ul><h3>Etiology</h3><ul><li>genetic vulnerability to psychosis</li><li>cognitive biases (e.g., jumping to conclusions)</li></ul><h3>Treatment</h3><ul><li>antipsychotic medication</li><li>CBT targeting delusional beliefs</li></ul><h3>Differential Diagnosis</h3><ul><li><strong>vs. Schizophrenia:</strong> schizophrenia includes hallucinations, disorganized speech, negative symptoms, and impairment.</li><li><strong>vs. OCD:</strong> OCD beliefs usually recognized as irrational; delusions are fixed false beliefs.</li><li><strong>vs. Paranoid Personality Disorder:</strong> PPD involves suspiciousness without fixed delusions.</li></ul>
      </div>
    </article>
    
